# Renderer2DSystem

## Purpose
Each frame: clears the screen, reads all in-frame draw events (quads, sprites, text, UI quads,
UI text), builds a transformed quad per draw, orders them, and submits them to the GPU as indexed
draw calls via the DirectX 11 backend.

On the first frame, allocates dynamic GPU vertex and index buffers and resolves default shaders
from ResourceMapSingletonComponent. Lazy-initializes by deferring RendererDataSingletonComponent
on the first frame and returning; rendering begins from the second frame.

## Y-up world & the texture flip
World space is **Y-up**: +Y is up on screen, matching the gameplay/transform convention. Vertex
positions are never negated; the camera projections map world/UI space to the screen directly.
DirectX samples textures with V increasing downward, so a Y-up world quad would sample its texture
upside down — **world draws compensate by flipping the V texture coordinate** (QuadData's flipTexV,
gated on Texture2D::FlipY(); true on DirectX11, false on the Testing backend). UI draws never flip V:
the UI canvas is y-down and is placed by the UICameraSingletonComponent's inverted ortho.

World **text** is reflected about its own anchor (AppendString's reflectAnchorY, gated on
Texture2D::FlipY()): the font lays glyphs out top-to-bottom in a y-down local space, so reflecting a
world string about its anchor makes it read top-to-bottom on the Y-up screen while keeping glyph
textures upright — no per-glyph V flip needed. UI text is laid out directly (no reflection).

Draws happen in two passes within a single cleared frame (ADR 0005):
- **World pass** — quads, sprites, and text are sorted by their render sort key (the world-space Y of
  each entity's local bottom edge, supplied on the draw event). For the Y-up world the order is
  **descending**: higher Y (further back) draws first, so lower-Y geometry (nearer the camera bottom)
  draws in front. Drawn through the gameplay OrthographicCameraComponent (which pans/zooms with input).
- **UI pass** — UI quads and text are drawn after the world so UI is always on top, through the
  screen-space UICameraSingletonComponent rather than the gameplay camera, ordered (ascending) by the
  nesting level packed in the UI transform's Z. The view-projection is swapped to the UI camera by
  re-uploading the shared device-level constant buffer (no second clear, which would wipe the world
  pass). The UI pass is skipped while the UI camera is absent (the first frame before UIRenderSystem
  creates it). Each UI draw carries a window-pixel clip rect; a clip change flushes the current batch
  and narrows the scissor (RendererAPI SetScissor), masking clipped sub-trees. The world pass runs with
  the full-window scissor set each frame in Begin().

UI quads sample the per-event UV sub-rect (so nine-slice cells map to their texture region); world
draws use the full texture or the sprite's coords. Consecutive draws that share a texture are merged
into one indexed draw call; a texture change flushes the current batch.

Strings emit one glyph quad per drawable character, advancing the pen by each glyph's metrics. A UI
string event carries a typewriter reveal count (m_VisibleChars): -1 draws every character, while N
draws only glyphs whose source index is < N (spaces and newlines still consume an index). The pen
layout is unaffected by the cutoff — it is computed from the full string by UIRenderSystem — so
revealing more characters never reflows the ones already shown. World text always draws in full.

## Input Components
| Component | Access |
|---|---|
| EngineConfigSingletonComponent | read |
| OrthographicCameraComponent | read |
| UICameraSingletonComponent | read |
| ResourceMapSingletonComponent | read |
| DrawQuadInFrameEvent | read |
| DrawSpriteInFrameEvent | read |
| DrawStringInFrameEvent | read |
| DrawUIQuadInFrameEvent | read |
| DrawUIStringInFrameEvent | read |
| RendererDataSingletonComponent | write |

## Output Components
| Component | Access | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| RendererDataSingletonComponent | write / add (deferred) | Holds GPU buffer handles and default shaders; created on first frame |
